# Create name vector of true factor variables so can leave them out of numeric conversions
fact_var <- c("Cluster", "PurchApp", "UAPurch", "myself", "significanto", "child", "father", "brother", "friend", "femalefammem", 
              "womennofam", "sportsbra", "headwear", "footwear", "shirt", "shorts", "outerwear", "pants", "other")

#create numeric data
dat_num <- dat %>% 
  # Remove true factor variables
  select(-fact_var) %>% 
  
  #Convert likert scale variables from section 1 survey data to character numbers
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "strongly disagree", "1"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "moderately disagree", "2"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "slightly disagree", "3"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "neutral", "4"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "slightly agree", "5"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "moderately agree", "6"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "strongly agree", "7"))) %>%
  
  #Convert likert scale variables from marketing effects to character numbers
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "strong negative influence", "1"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "moderate negative influence", "2"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "slight negative influence", "3"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "no influence", "4"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "slight positive influence", "5"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "moderate positive influence", "6"))) %>% 
  mutate_all(list( ~str_replace(., "strong positive influence", "7")))

2 Preliminary EDA

Now that we have sorted our data and cleaned it of NAs, it’s time to take a look at the questions we are hoping to answer over this project. Before beginning its important to remember a few key facts about this case:

  1. This survey only includes female Under Armour customers.
  2. Under Armour began this market research due to poor performance from their initial launch of the women’s apparel lines.
  3. We are specifically looking at our exercise and sports apparel, but that may not be our key selling point / loss point.
  4. Most apparel consumption is driven by materialistic or hedonistic values

2.1 Questions for Exploration

  1. Are female Under Armour consumers primarily anti-materialists, hedonists, environmentalists, or fitness enthusiasts?
  2. Does consumer knowledge of product performance impact brand attitude?
  3. Does consumer knowledge of product performance impact motivate purchases?
  4. Should Under Armour sell to brick-and-mortar or online?
  5. What type of advertising and promotions help sales the most?
  6. Are there different segments in the female Under Armour market?

2.2 Variable Choices

There are many variables that are on similar topics that can be used to cover that topic entirely. One example is “I like Under Armour” and “I think Under Armour is a good brand” (Brandatt1 and Brandatt2). These are repetitive so we do not need to use both.

3.1.1 Comments

We already chewed through a lot of this in the preliminary EDA, but it is time to lay down some thoughts about the data we will be combing through further.

Our survey questions that are on the likert scale are all numeric, including income and marketing questions. Our clusters of participants, exercise per week, minutes per exercise, and purchasing questions on types of products purchased and who they were for are all factors. This makes sense because the cluster is made up of qualitative groups and the purchase questions are binary. Let’s take another look at our exploratory questions.

3.1.2 Questions for Exploration

  1. Are female Under Armour consumers primarily anti-materialists, hedonists, environmentalists, or fitness enthusiasts?
  • Most participants are Environmentalists, followed by Hedonists, Fitness Enthusiasts, and Anti-Materialists
    • We should make a histogram to show this off some more
    • How much crossover is between each group?
  1. Does consumer knowledge of product performance impact brand attitude?
  2. Does consumer knowledge of product performance impact motivate purchases?
  3. Should Under Armour sell to brick-and-mortar or online?
  • We saw in earlier correlations that people who had intent to purchase and who liked Under Armour had a higher positive relationship with brick and mortar stores. This will be explored further in the multi-variate portion of the EDA.
  1. What type of advertising and promotions help sales the most?
  • Will be looked into next, especially in Multi-Variate
  1. Are there different segments in the female Under Armour market?
  • I think we will find that there are. The Cluster variable gives us what I believe our segments will be.

3.1.3 A Note on Handling Likert Data

We will be treating this data as Likert item data as opposed to Likert scale data. This means that the data will be observed as ordinal data rather than ratio data. This means we cannot be certain about equal spacing between the points (EX. The average of strongly disagree and slightly disagree cannot be said to be moderately disagree). This is why we are using the medians for the data as well.

3.2.2.1 Takeaways

  • 50% of applicants have a household income of $59,999 or below. This is the 3rd lowest income option.
  • Any participant older than 50 is an outlier. 50% of participants are between 20 and about 30 years of age.
  • Almost everyone feels neutral to strongly agreed that Under Armour is a desirable brand.
  • Most people disagreed that materialism is very important to them.
    • I think hedonism data is going to be hard to track because most people probably are unable to accurately assess negative characteristics about themselves
    • This however means we should probably avoid making our image based on material wealth
  • Most people believe they will benefit from wearing performance sports apparel
    • This is unsurprising because it is a survey of people who have purchased performance sports apparel
  • Most people agreed that they wanted a product with a good aesthetic and value for money.

3.3 Multivariate Non-Graphical EDA

3.3.1 Correlations

# Survey Questions + Purchasing Intent + Location of Purchase
cor(data[c(2,6,9,12,15,17,19,27,31,32,23,35,37,45,44)],use = "pairwise.complete.obs") %>%
  corrplot.mixed(lower = "shade", upper = "number", tl.pos = "lt", diag = "u", tl.col ="navy", tl.srt = 45, outline = TRUE, tl.cex=.8, number.cex = .7, number.digits = 2,)

Across the board positive correlations to the survey data and purchase intent. There were a few standout correlations:

  • Holding acquisition of items in high regard(materialism1) had a correlation with placing importance on prestige (success1).
  • Wanting socially just companies (Csr3) and finding protecting the environment important (environ3) are highly correlated.
  • Supporting women’s issues (Cause3) and expecting social responsibility from companies (Csr3) are highly correlated.
  • Placing importance on product quality (Prodqual3) and believing that sports apparel has benefits (Knowledge2) are highly correlated.
  • More people intending to purchase products (prodpur2) are interested in Retail (Retail) over Online (Online).
  • People who like Under Armour are more likely to shop in store than online.

4.1 1 Sales, Peers, and Family opinion impact purchase behavior the most

#Take all advertisement options, list it on the Y axis, fill by the choices 1-7, x axis is just a 100% scale
ad_data <- data %>% 
  group_by(`family`,`sale`,`peers`) %>% 
  summarize(n = n()) %>% 
  gather(Advertisement, Response, -c(n)) %>% 
  #mutate response to have better legend names
  mutate(Response = ifelse(Response == "1", "Negative Strong Influence", 
                    ifelse(Response == "2", "Negative Moderate Influence",
                    ifelse(Response == "3", "Negative Slight Influence",
                    ifelse(Response == "4", "No Influence",
                    ifelse(Response == "5", "Positive Minor Influence",
                    ifelse(Response == "6", "Positive Moderate Influence",
                    ifelse(Response == "7", "Positive Strong Influence", "NULL"
                           ))))))))%>% 
  #mutate advertisement to have better names
  mutate(Advertisement = ifelse(Advertisement == "sale","Item On Sale",
                         ifelse(Advertisement == "family","Family Opinion",
                         ifelse(Advertisement == "peers","Peer Opinion", "NULL"
                                ))))%>%
  #plot starts here
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Advertisement, y = n, fill = Response)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank()) + 
     labs(x = "Advertisement Option", title = "Family, Peer, and Sale Advertisement most positively impact purchasing", fill = "Participant Response")

4.3 3 While Brick and Mortar beats out Online, both are favored.

# Does our primary demographic enjoy online or brick and mortar more?
store_data <- data %>%
     mutate(storefront = 
                     ifelse(Online == "5", "Online",
                     ifelse(Online == "6", "Online",
                     ifelse(Online == "7", "Online",                           
                     ifelse(Retail == "5", "Brick and Mortar",
                     ifelse(Retail == "6", "Brick and Mortar",
                     ifelse(Retail == "7", "Brick and Mortar","Other"                            
                     ))))))) %>%
     mutate(income = 
                     ifelse(income == "1", "below $20,000",
                     ifelse(income == "2", "$20,000 - $39,000",
                     ifelse(income == "3", "$40,000 - $59,999",                           
                     ifelse(income == "4", "$60,000 - $79,999",
                     ifelse(income == "5", "$80,000 - $99,999",
                     ifelse(income == "6", "$100,000 - $149,999",
                     ifelse(income == "7", "$150,000 - $199,999","$200,000 or above"                            
                     )))))))) %>%
     filter(UAPurch == "yes" & fact_age == "1" & (storefront == "Online" | storefront == "Brick and Mortar")) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = storefront, fill = income)) +
   geom_bar(position = "stack") +
   coord_flip() +
     labs(x = "Storefront style",y = "18-24 year olds who feel positively", title = "18-24 year olds would rather shop online", fill = "Income level")
